This confirms not only that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already very widespread, but provides details that fossils usually cannot provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
The scientists say that the plumage of this animal was chestnut brown on top and pale or carotenoid on the underside.
This discovery also allows us to better understand the evolution of feathers in birds.
Given that dinosaur feathers do not have a fully developed shaft, which is called a rachis, but do show other characteristics of feathers – barbs and barbules – the researchers have deduced that the rachis was probably a later evolutionary development than these other characteristics.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used in flight but rather for temperature regulation or display. Researchers have suggested that, even if it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample shows an adult plumage and not the down of a chick.
The scientists specify that it is indeed the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, but the sample reveals a plumage belonging to an adult individual, and not to a young one.
